Prostomium conical, large, 1/3 of the peristomium width. Tiny palpode; eyespots absent. Peristomium large, same width and 1.5x longer than chaetigers 1 and 2 (
Fig. 5A, C
). Nuchal organs not everted. Proboscis globularshaped, strongly papillated with robust papillae (
Fig. 5B
).

Thorax rounded, with 11 chaetigers. Chaetiger 1 uniramous. Capillaries on notopodia of chaetigers 1–11 and on neuropodia of chaetigers 2–10; hooded hooks on neuropodia of chaetiger 11 (
Fig. 5G
). Peristomium and chaetigers 1–3 strongly tessellated dorsally, with deep grooves on epithelium; subsequent chaetigers smooth (
Fig. 5B, F
). Deep lateral groove (LG) on peristomium and chaetigers 1–4 (
Fig. 5C
). Chaetigers 1–4 not biannulate, slightly rectangular, straight, 1.2x wider than long, chaetiger 4 the widest, with deep intersegmental groove (
Fig. 5A, F, G
). Chaetigers 5–11 not biannulate, square-like, as wide as long, straight, with deep intersegmental groove (
Fig. 5A, F, G
). Chaetal bundles numerous (~30 chaetae) and dorso-lateral throughout thorax; deep and large cavity of capillaries insertion (
Fig. 5F–G
). Chaetae emerging from middle of chaetiger. Lateral organs very small, visible only after staining. A pair of genital pores between chaetigers 7/8, 8/9, 9/10, 10/11, 11/12, and 12/13 (
Fig. 5F
). Transition between thorax and abdomen very subtle, marked by Methyl Green staining and slightly change in shape of chaetigers.

Abdomen rounded, with capillaries on notopodia up to chaetiger 24 and hooded hooks on neuropodia of all abdominal chaetigers (
Fig. 5D, G
). Chaetigers 1.2x wider than long (
Fig. 5D–E
). Chaetae and hooded hooks emerging from last third of chaetiger. Notopodial lobes absent on chaetigers with capillaries (
Fig. 5D
); small, poorly developed, and dorso-lateral on chaetigers with hooded hooks (~10 hooded hooks each fascicle). Neuropodial lobes small, poorly developed, and ventral; distance between lobes reduced along the abdomen (~40 hooded hooks each fascicle) (
Fig. 5E
). Noto-and neuropodial hooded hooks with two rows of teeth above main fang (2–1), main fang slightly curved, large, and with a rounded tip; narrow and smooth hood (
Fig. 5H–I
). Branchiae unknown. Pygidium unknown.

Methyl Green staining pattern (MGSP).
Thorax staining darker than abdomen, abdomen staining light green without any evident pattern. A dark and thin band on anterior margin of chaetiger 4 present (
Fig. 5F–G
). The posterior region (posterior to chaetal bundle) of chaetiger seven up to anterior region (anterior to chaetal bundle) of chaetiger 11 staining darker than the remaining ones (
Fig. 5F–G
). Chaetiger 11 with a dark and thin band near the division with chaetiger 12 (
Fig. 5F–G
).
